segments.text: A senior was just, he was everything.
A freshman was nothing.
Why that comparative democracy?
I guess because we all sort of looked alike, dressed alike, did the same things together.
And there were so few immodulants of, well, you knew my classmate of mine whose father was a Buick dealer, and he had a Buick.
He got it his senior year.
He didn't have one before then, because he couldn't have one until he was a senior.
But there were some from successful business fathers, but I can't tell you what any ratios were.
I would just call it...
middle America to, I hesitate to use the word lower middle class and upper middle class.
I sort of like the difference between a medium steak and a medium rare.
I don't know what a medium rare steak is.
I know what a rare is and I know what a medium is.
I would say it was medium, middle class America.
I've always thought, too, that what mattered is were you an Aggie or were you not.
That's right.
It didn't make any difference where you were from, what you were studying, who you were.
It made absolutely no difference at all.
The only difference was that even as a freshman, the lowest form of humanity on the face of the earth, except for every graduate from the University of Texas,
What were the highest status student?

And there was no, if the corps commander, even though more come to my outfit or to your outfit and tried to exercise his authority as the corps commander, there was a battery commander there, a troop commander.
He was the boss.
What were the highest prestige students?
It was federalism at its best.
Oh, okay.
That's very good.
Okay.
What were the highest prestige students?
offices, attainments?
Well, I think there were some that got in as who's who.
Oh, no, no, no, no, no, no.
In your own mind, which did you and your colleagues most respect?
The corps commander, the head yell leader, the what?
The corps commander was very popular.
Joe Slicker, in my opinion, was the most popular man in my class.
He was a battery commander, and he was commander, captain of the RVs, of course, here.
I think he was the most popular man in my class, although the Corps commander was very well liked as well.
Bill Becker was his name.
Were there other tasks that had... We paid no attention in the outfits to the battalion staff or to the regimental.
The regimental commander of the Coast Guard was in my back.
or not to do anything.
Tom Haygood was his name.
And he lived, he was a classmate of mine.
In my back was a regimental planner.
Okay, we're now to the, we're right near the end and we're to the end.
The seniors were the ones in authority.
My senior year, there was a flu epidemic that hit the campus.
And at the mess hall, at the evening mess one day,
The tally of attention and announcements were made that there would be a meeting of the senior class in DeWare Fieldhouse immediately after mass.
That's all.
So after mass we went down there.
Bill Becker was up there, and he was a corps commander, and a couple of others.
And the hospital was full.
We had kids sick in the hallways in the dorms, and they were being ministered to by fellow students.
So real epidemic.
And the announcement was made, we've got a problem with this flu.
And it's near Christmas time, about a week before Christmas holiday started.
And they said, we think we ought to shut her down and go home and get off this campus, those of us that can get off.
And what do you think about that?
Everybody was in favor of that.
It was a smart thing to do.
Somebody said, well, go get baritrax.
So he didn't live very far.
He just lived on the other side of what is now G. Raleigh White.
And so he got the nickname because he was just the hulk of a guy.
And he was the dean.
Talk about making the dean's team, not an A&M.
It worked the other way.
He didn't want anything to do.
But anyway, here comes Bartrax and puts him up on stage.
Somebody says, let's hear it for Dean Bolton.
And Dean, Dean, Dean, he gave a yell.
And so I said to Dean, Dean, the way this flu is bad, we have decided we're going to, the school's coming to an end.
And he said, well, let's talk this over.
And Dean, we have decided we're going home tomorrow.
We're going back to our outfits now and tell everybody to pack and go home.
And that was that.
Went back to my outside.
Got the first sergeant in the house.
Let's get all the juniors out.
And we got, we met with them, said, pass the word, we're leaving.
School's out.
And we left.
All right, to the important part.
That was pretty important.
When you talk about insurrection now, that was not insurrection.
It just was an assumption of authority, and Bartrax Bolton and T.O.
Walton were smart enough to know that if the senior class had decided that.
The better.
Well, that caused me to bounce back to academics.
How common was it that somebody cheated?
Well, I suppose it happened.
But was it common?
Not to my knowledge.
Did you all have test files or anything like that of old tests?
I never saw one.
Never.
Nor did I ever hear of one becoming available.
Never.
But you don't remember any stunts where somebody got a copy of a test or anything like that?
Never came to my attention.
I've not heard of it.
I might have been delighted to have a copy of it, but no.
I never really, I don't believe, I can't say that it didn't happen because I have no recollection of it ever having happened.
As you look back, were there some courses you now believe were more important to your future than others?
Oh, I think so.
I think so.
The fact of the matter is, a great deal that prepared me for my turning out to be a trial lawyer.
I tried lawsuits for 47 years.
was that I debated.
A&M was a nothing in debating when I got there.
And a senior in I went over to Austin, and when I was a freshman, we won the Southwest Congress debating championship.
It was a first for A&M to even be there, much less to win it.
Who was there, was there a particular important coach or teacher?
A fellow in the English department was sort of the sponsor, but C.O.
Spriggs was in there.
We called him Cosine, Cosine Spriggs.
S-P-R-I-G-G-S?
Yes.
And his C-O was initial, so C-O-S, and we called him Cosine.
Cosine, right.
Cosine Spriggs.
And he had a fellow whose name I can't remember.
So did you do that for all four years?
No, we only debated for two years.
Then intercollegiate debating became sort of passe, and it went to what they call roundtable, discussion type things.
And we did have a round table club at A&M.
And I started it in my junior year, but it didn't last.
We debated Oxford on the campus over in the physics theater.
And the place was jammed.
And it was joke telling.
That's the way the English debated.
It was very light.
They'd announce the subject and then very rarely touch on it.
It was a, I spent a lot of time in the library researching on the subjects.
Describe Cushing Library.
Well of course it was a grand old place and the librarian was Tommy Mayo and he used to call me cousin.
Did class rank matter in the library?
I don't believe so.
If you were studying?
Okay, the important questions now.
What did it mean to you that you went to Texas A&M as you look back on your life?
A little history.
I was 12, 13 years old.
I was sitting on a curb in the 400 block of South Adams.
And I was 12, 13 years old, under a street light.
It was summertime.
And I looked around.
The fellas that I played ball with, we wound up being the high school baseball team.
I can remember that the pitcher, his name was Patterson, his father sold peanut patties, not peanut brittle.
They were as big as, and they were just peanut patties, sugar with peanuts in them.
Some of the men were unemployed.
There just wasn't much.
And I thought to myself, and I give God the credit for this, Mel, you've got to get out of here.
Now, you're an American.
This just evolves over time.
You're entitled to a chance.
And that's all you got coming to you is a chance.
And I got on that train and went to College Station.
And I went to see E.E.
McQuillan.
And A&M gave me a chance to get a college education.
And I am in their debt.
I will never be able to repay it.
I have tried in every way.
I'm a founding member of the President's Endowed Scholarship Program.
I have provided an athletic scholarship for I just don't know how long.
I am a member of the associates program.
I am a member of the heritage program.
And just A&M, I teach a lot of Bible classes.
And I tell them, I say, the most important
things in my life are easily spelled out for you.
First of all, God is the most important person to me.
Then my next most important is my family.
And then not my church, but A&M.
Then the church in there close.
And I just, A&M gave me a chance.
I think that the
Those were four preparatory years that provide you with...
I never had any trouble studying in law school.
I never had any trouble with the discipline in the Army.
I liked it.
I liked it.
I remember from my junior ROTC days in junior high school reading a manual on military courtesy and discipline.
Military discipline is the willful
and cheerful obedience to orders.
Now that sort of fits God as well.
If you love me, he says, keep my commandments.
It's the willful and cheerful obedience to orders.
I've never forgotten it.
So I was able to work under lawyers, learn things from them.
I was a distinguished law student, a C-plus student at A&M.
The high man on the bar exam, 194 others took it, beat me three points.
And when I came out and I lost school, I got a chance.
I got a chance.
And that was the second chance that I got.
And A&M gave me the first one.
And I tell people, I said I was born American and born white.
I started out ahead of everybody else that was not American and was not white.
And there's just no question about it.
White man has had an advantage over the black man from the beginning.
So I just feel ever so grateful.
I really have a grateful heart.
I might have been or not been a lot of things, but always been grateful.
I have a grateful heart to God.
and to my family and to A&M.
